HEADWORD: Cordiality
<hw>Cor*dial"i*ty</hw> <pr>(k⟦ocir⟧r*j⟦acr⟧l"⟦icr⟧*t⟦ycr⟧ ⟦or⟧
k⟦ocir⟧r`d⟦icr⟧*⟦acr⟧l"-; 106)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Cordialities</plw> <pr>(-t⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[LL.
<ets>cordialitas</ets>, fr. <ets>cordialis</ets> sincere: cf. F.
<ets>cordialit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Relation to the
heart.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That the ancients had any respect of <qex>cordiality</qex> or
reference unto the heart, will much be doubted.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T.
Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Sincere affection and kindness; warmth of regard;
heartiness.</def> <rj><au>Motley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cordialize</ent>⟦br⟧
